      "content": "but that \"non-standard usage\" is exactly the point. they use coded language specifically so it doesn't sound like a neutral economic concept to the general public. they need it to sound like a pop song so it flows through the airwaves without triggering any alarms. if they used the term \"liquidity injection\" in a radio hit, everyone would freak out. but \"sweetness\"? \"working late\"? it's perfect cover.\n\nthink about the word \"espresso\" itself. an espresso is a concentrated shot, right? a quick, intense burst of energy. isn't that basically a metaphor for a massive, sudden stimulus injection designed to spike the system before a crash? look at the way the chorus repeats with that specific tempo—it matches the frequency of short-term liquidity pulses. if you cross-reference the lyrical cadence with the timing of the recent treasury auctions, does it not look like a synchronized signal?",
